## LDAP Configuration

LDAP authentication is disabled by default. To enable it, add the following to the systemd service file at `/etc/systemd/system/cmdb-web.service` under `[Service]`:

```ini
Environment=LDAP_ENABLED=true
Environment=LDAP_SERVER=ldap://your.ad.server.corp.pvt
Environment=LDAP_PORT=389
Environment=LDAP_USE_SSL=false
Environment=LDAP_BIND_DN=CN=svc-cmdb,OU=Service Accounts,DC=corp,DC=pvt
Environment=LDAP_BIND_PASS=<service account password>
Environment=LDAP_BASE_DN=DC=corp,DC=pvt
Environment=LDAP_USER_FILTER=(sAMAccountName={username})
Environment=LDAP_EMAIL_ATTR=mail
Environment=LDAP_DISPLAY_ATTR=displayName
```

After editing, reload and restart:
```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart cmdb-web
```

LDAP users are auto-provisioned in the local users table on first login. They will have read-only access by default; an admin must grant admin role if needed via Admin → Users.

